<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-562-951  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 562 951.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>ACM Transactions on Database Systems  Sept 1990 v15 n3 p341(18).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Scaling up output capacity and performance results frominformation systems prototypes. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Westland, J. Christopher.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Prototyping of an information system is valuable because it canpredict problems and end-user satisfaction with a system early inthe development process.andP;  Scaling up is the process of inferencefrom prototype to full-scale information system to reportinformation to the end user.andP;  The factors that determine whetheror not reported information is useful are how much information isreported, how aesthetically appealing the reporting is, theproportion of relevant or useful data reported, and how much ofthe reported data is useful or relevant.andP;  There are three sourcesof events that produce output of information for the end user:passage of a time interval; an internal or external event occurs;the end user requests information.andP;  The three problem areas whichoften receive inadequate attention by the database designer arethe potential for end-user information overload; the adequacy ofretrieval performance; and the ability of output hardware andemployees to handle retrieval record volumes.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PrototypeInformation Storage and RetrievalPerformance MeasurementData Base Design.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>